Factory Design Pattern:
- "Tell me what you want, I'll create it for you — you don't need to know how it's made."
Core idea: Move object creation logic out of client code into a dedicated factory.

With Factory
    Client depends only on interface
    Creation centralized in one place
    Add new type = modify only factory
    Easy to mock/swap implementations
    Factory is open for extension

When To Use Factory?
    Object creation logic is complex or conditional
    You need to decouple client from concrete implementations
    Multiple implementations of same interface exist
    Object type determined at runtime
    You want centralized control over object creation

Avoid when: Only one implementation exists and creation is trivial — factory adds unnecessary complexity.

Built-in Factories in Java
    // NumberFormat Factory
    NumberFormat fmt = NumberFormat.getInstance(Locale.US);
    NumberFormat currency = NumberFormat.getCurrencyInstance();

    // Calendar Factory
    Calendar cal = Calendar.getInstance();

    // Collections Factory
    List<String> list = List.of("a", "b");          // Java 9+
    Set<String> set = Set.of("x", "y");

    // Path Factory
    Path path = Path.of("/usr/local/bin");

    // Optional Factory
    Optional<String> opt = Optional.of("value");
    Optional<String> empty = Optional.empty();

    // ExecutorService Factory
    ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);
    ExecutorService cached = Executors.newCachedThreadPool();

Built-in Factories in SpringBoot
    // BeanFactory — core Spring factory
    BeanFactory factory = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");

    // LoggerFactory (SLF4J)
    Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MyService.class);

============
Try Springboot way to implement Factory pattern.

Version 4 — Registry-Based Factory (Production-Ready, fully OCP compliant)
// Registry — no switch, no if-else, fully extensible
@Component
public class PaymentProcessorFactory {

    private final Map<String, PaymentProcessor> registry = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    // Auto-registers all PaymentProcessor beans
    public PaymentProcessorFactory(List<PaymentProcessor> processors) {
        processors.forEach(p -> registry.put(p.getType().toUpperCase(), p));
    }

    public PaymentProcessor getProcessor(String type) {
        PaymentProcessor processor = registry.get(type.toUpperCase());
        if (processor == null) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("No processor registered for: " + type);
        }
        return processor;
    }

    // Runtime extensibility
    public void registerProcessor(String type, PaymentProcessor processor) {
        registry.put(type.toUpperCase(), processor);
    }
}

// Processors as Spring beans — auto-registered
@Service
public class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentProcessor {
    @Override public String getType() { return "CREDIT"; }
    @Override public void process(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Credit Card: ₹" + amount);
    }
}

@Service
public class UpiPayment implements PaymentProcessor {
    @Override public String getType() { return "UPI"; }
    @Override public void process(double amount) {
        System.out.println("UPI: ₹" + amount);
    }
}

// Adding new payment type — ZERO changes to factory or client!
@Service
public class NetBankingPayment implements PaymentProcessor {
    @Override public String getType() { return "NETBANKING"; }
    @Override public void process(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Net Banking: ₹" + amount);
    }
}

// Clean service
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderService {

    private final PaymentProcessorFactory factory;

    public void processPayment(String type, double amount) {
        factory.getProcessor(type).process(amount);
    }
}

** Adding a new payment type = just create a new @Service class. Nothing else changes.
** Golden Rule: Factory should return an interface, never a concrete class. Client should never need instanceof after getting the object.
